## What I did

Implemented `applyBenchmarkTask(db, now)` in `/Users/rom.iluz/Dev/sql-hidden-cost/benchmark/runs/ast-bench-v1/invoice-dispute-workflow/claude-code/repeat-1/mongo/workspace/src/workflow.mjs`. It mutates the in-memory `db` arrays then returns `buildPortalView(db)`. Everything is sourced from `request = db.workflow_requests[0]` — no hardcoded status/owner/signal/message strings.

- **workflow_state**: one doc with `requestId`, `accountId`, `status = request.expectedOutcome`, `title`, `nextStep`, a copy of `riskSignals` (order preserved via `.map(s => ({...s}))`), plus `_id`/`createdAt`/`updatedAt` from `now`.
- **owner_tasks**: one task per `request.ownerGroups` entry, in order, each with `ownerGroup`, `title` (`"${ownerGroup}: ${request.title}"`), `status: "open"`, and `dueAt` derived as `now + (index+1)h` ISO string.
- **customer_messages**: one doc with `body = request.customerMessage`, `customerVisible: true`, `channel: "portal"`, `_id`/`createdAt`.
- **audit_events**: one doc with `event: "invoice-dispute.activated"`, `actor`, `message`, `customerVisible: true`, `occurredAt`/`createdAt`.

Note: I used `request.ownerGroups.length` (4 groups in the fixture; the task brief mentioned "4 groups" while the data has 4 ownerGroups) — the loop iterates the actual array so the count always matches the fixture. (The fixture has 6 riskSignals; the test deep-equals all of them and passes.)

